2.

Summarize the data by calculating the mean, variance, for each column and the correlation between each pair (eg. x1 and y1, x2 and y2, etc) (Hint: use the fBasics() package!)

library(fBasics)
## Loading required package: timeDate
## Loading required package: timeSeries

ameans
##       x1       x2       x3       x4       y1       y2       y3       y4 
## 9.000000 9.000000 9.000000 9.000000 7.500909 7.500909 7.500000 7.500909
avariances <- colVars(data)
avariances
##        x1        x2        x3        x4        y1        y2        y3 
## 11.000000 11.000000 11.000000 11.000000  4.127269  4.127629  4.122620 
##        y4

acor <- cor(ax,ay)

## x1  0.8164205  0.8162365  0.8162867 -0.3140467
## x2  0.8164205  0.8162365  0.8162867 -0.3140467

diag(acor)
## [1] 0.8164205 0.8162365 0.8162867 0.8165214

“ameans” shows all means and “avariances” shows all variances of each column variables. Since “acor” derives all possible correlation combinations between {x1, … ,x4} and {y1, …, y4} respectively, I used “diag()” function for specified matrix combinations of {x1,y1}, {x2,y2}, {x3,y3}, and {x4,y4}.

3.

Create scatter plots for each \(x, y\) pair of data. < 1st Method : “ggplot” >

almgp1 <- ggplot(data, mapping=aes(x=x1, y=y1)) + geom_point() + labs(title="Pair x1 & y1") + stat_smooth(method="lm", col = "rosybrown2", se=FALSE)

8.

In text, summarize the lesson of Anscombe’s Quartet and what it says about the value of data visualization.

By calculating critical factors of each variables and models in this data set, each pairwise correlation of {x1, y1}, {x2, y2}, {x3, y3}, and {x4, y4} shows quite similar theoretical results;

  • mean of {x1}, {x2}, {x3}, {y4} = 9.0,
  • mean of {x1}, {x2}, {x3}, {y4} = 7.5,
  • variance of {x1}, {x2}, {x3}, {y4} = 11,
  • variance of {y1, y2, y3, y4} = {4.127, 4.127, 4.127, 4.123},
  • correlation coefficient of {x1, y1}, {x2, y2}, {x3, y3}, {x4, y4} = 0.816,
  • R-squared values of lm{x1, y1}, lm{x2, y2}, lm{x3, y3}, {x4,y4} ≈ 0.66,
  • Fitted models : y = 0.5x + 3.0 for all {x1,y1}, {x2,y2}, {x3,y3}, {x4,y4}.

However, visualizing the data with scatter plot, it is clear to notice that they all differ from each other. For instance, the Pair x1 & y1 graph has entities that look almost randomly distributed to form a upward slope, while the Pair x2 & y2 entities form a upward curve, and the Pair x3 & y3 and x4 & y4 show their significant outliers. This interesting ambivalence tells us not only the importance of data visualization, but also the requirement and possibility of further approaches, to understand the data clearly and meet our analytic goals efficiently.
